1
00:00:01,246 --> 00:00:18,449
Foundation Course 1 Talk 2 The First Noble Truth of Suffering Conditioned States When we look at any object in the world, be it natural or man-made, we tend to see it as a whole, a total or integral thing.

2
00:00:19,291 --> 00:00:20,533
Take for instance the car.

3
00:00:21,574 --> 00:00:27,682
We see it parked or moving, we see it as an object in itself, we see it as one substantial thing.

4
00:00:29,085 --> 00:00:30,746
But this is just a concept.

5
00:00:30,980 --> 00:00:33,463
we lose sight of the fact that it's made up of parts.

6
00:00:34,363 --> 00:00:46,436
It's only when the car breaks down that we remember, or perhaps realise for the first time, that, if we're not mechanically minded, that it is an object made up of many other objects, all in relationship to each other.

7
00:00:47,758 --> 00:00:50,881
Only when all these pieces are assembled do we call it a car.

8
00:00:52,003 --> 00:00:54,905
The petrol pump is hidden away, hardly known by most drivers.

9
00:00:55,487 --> 00:00:56,548
Suddenly the car stops.

10
00:00:56,968 --> 00:00:58,590
We call the services.

11
00:00:58,637 --> 00:01:00,741
The mechanic says, it's the petrol pump.

12
00:01:01,603 --> 00:01:05,430
We realise this little object is crucial to the well-being of the car.

13
00:01:06,253 --> 00:01:13,707
We realise that this car we once took as a whole and entire is simply an intricate relationship of parts to parts.

14
00:01:15,871 --> 00:01:19,920
This might be a layman's view of a car, but specialists may see it in a different light.

15
00:01:20,085 --> 00:01:22,549
The mechanic sees it as transmission and bodywork.

16
00:01:23,150 --> 00:01:28,496
The metallurgist as a collection of different materials, metals, plastics, natural substances such as wood and rubber.

17
00:01:29,457 --> 00:01:33,563
Scientists see it as molecular structures or subatomic particles, whatever.

18
00:01:34,043 --> 00:01:41,334
The point is that the car can be pulled apart and heaped into different piles depending on how you look at it, how you perceive it.

19
00:01:43,557 --> 00:01:50,025
When it comes to the human being, it is astounding how many ways this poor being has been divided and subdivided.

20
00:01:50,224 --> 00:01:56,933
Every religious, philosophical and psychological school East and West has its own definition or division of the human being.

21
00:01:58,055 --> 00:02:04,043
In the West, materialist biologists and behavioural psychologists see the human as simply a collection of physical parts.

22
00:02:04,924 --> 00:02:08,689
Mind or personality is simply brain, grey matter indeed.

23
00:02:10,192 --> 00:02:14,798
Freudians categorise humans as a process moving from one stage of development to another.

24
00:02:15,655 --> 00:02:19,979
Social psychologists and sociologists see the person in terms of relationship to others.

25
00:02:21,221 --> 00:02:26,104
Christianity and Islam say that it's more than just a body and mind.

26
00:02:26,665 --> 00:02:28,687
They posit an everlasting soul.

27
00:02:30,669 --> 00:02:36,355
Ever since the philosopher Descartes in the 17th century, we in the West have looked upon the human being essentially as a machine.

28
00:02:37,096 --> 00:02:45,645
Only recently have scientists begun to look at the human as an integrated circuit in holistic terms, rather than just a set of parts that happen to be together

29
00:02:45,945 --> 00:02:47,108
but work independently.

30
00:02:47,949 --> 00:02:50,431
The list of categorizations is endless.

31
00:02:52,014 --> 00:02:57,762
Now, as for the Buddha's point of view, everything arises from his own self-designated area of teaching.

32
00:02:58,802 --> 00:03:07,514
Whatever he knew about the human being, he confined what he said to the noble truths and to his aim to teach only the fact of suffering and the end of suffering.

33
00:03:08,355 --> 00:03:21,953
For the Buddha, it was of paramount importance to be able to pinpoint for people where their suffering arose and what in fact constituted suffering, so that the way or path leading to the end of suffering would be made clear to the listener.

34
00:03:22,914 --> 00:03:25,157
He simply wasn't interested in anything else.

35
00:03:26,019 --> 00:03:31,866
So, when we read the teachings of the Buddha, it's important to keep in mind what angle he's coming from.

36
00:03:34,006 --> 00:03:44,444
The Buddha divided the human being into what is known as the five khanda, translated as aggregates and sometimes a little unkindly as heaps.

37
00:03:44,465 --> 00:03:51,457
So, just as the metallurgist might divide the car into metals, plastic, rubber, glass and oils...

38
00:03:52,467 --> 00:04:00,936
The Buddha divided the human being into matter, sensations, perceptions, volitional formations and consciousness.

39
00:04:01,817 --> 00:04:07,582
And each category is to be seen as a heap of similar things, like five distinct scrap yards.

40
00:04:09,705 --> 00:04:14,491
Now, at base, the human is made of two separate phenomena, matter and mind.

41
00:04:15,551 --> 00:04:19,976
Matter is the body itself, the bones, muscles, blood and so on, including brain.

42
00:04:21,307 --> 00:04:28,357
But mind is different from matter, a more subtle phenomenon that infuses the body like dye in water.

43
00:04:29,637 --> 00:04:36,206
Matter is rupa in Pali, which is the language that all the scriptures of the Theravadan tradition of Buddhism are written in.

44
00:04:37,187 --> 00:04:39,672
It is a dialect of one of the ancient languages in India.

45
00:04:41,494 --> 00:04:46,521
However, here rupa, matter, not only refers to the actual physical matter...

46
00:04:46,619 --> 00:04:49,281
but to how the mind experiences this matter.

47
00:04:49,942 --> 00:04:51,824
And for the meditator this is very important.

48
00:04:54,086 --> 00:04:57,790
The mind infuses the body and comes in contact with matter.

49
00:04:58,872 --> 00:05:03,255
This contact, this interface we can say, is the base of mind.

50
00:05:03,857 --> 00:05:04,858
It is the sense base.

51
00:05:06,199 --> 00:05:11,665
It is at five points that mind comes to know matter, the five sense bases.

52
00:05:11,915 --> 00:05:18,940
For example, light, as a physical phenomena, the photons, strikes the retina in the eye.

53
00:05:19,882 --> 00:05:21,783
This is all that is known by the eye.

54
00:05:22,584 --> 00:05:27,829
Without the retina, without the eyes, a person simply does not know or experience light.

55
00:05:29,050 --> 00:05:35,076
When the photons are felt by the mind at the point of contact on the retina, mind experiences matter.

56
00:05:36,117 --> 00:05:40,521
So it is with all the other senses of touch, smelling,

57
00:05:41,598 --> 00:05:42,918
hearing and tasting.

58
00:05:45,341 --> 00:05:52,488
This initial contact with matter is experienced as a combination in varying degrees of what Buddhism calls four elements.

59
00:05:53,509 --> 00:05:57,113
They are descriptively known as earth, fire, water and air.

60
00:05:58,235 --> 00:06:03,620
The earth element refers to the quality of weight and is sensed as pressure, light or heavy.

61
00:06:04,641 --> 00:06:07,824
Fire is temperature from extreme heat to extreme cold.

62
00:06:08,985 --> 00:06:11,329
Water is cohesion or elasticity.

63
00:06:11,889 --> 00:06:13,151
It's what keeps things together.

64
00:06:14,553 --> 00:06:16,177
Air is movement, pure movement.

65
00:06:17,738 --> 00:06:23,107
The last two are difficult to experience purely by themselves, but can be done in meditation.

66
00:06:23,968 --> 00:06:29,918
The first two, pressure and temperature, are gross enough for us to be aware of even in daily life.

67
00:06:30,978 --> 00:06:37,930
When someone stands on our toes in the bus queue, that's the earth element we are experiencing at base sense level.

68
00:06:39,478 --> 00:06:48,733
When we touch a hot pan, handle, by mistake, what makes us howl is the fire element at the sense base, the nerve endings in the hand.

69
00:06:49,855 --> 00:07:01,774
It is only after this is sensed that the mind recognises it as pressure or heat, and then, if mind perceives signals as too much, we react to avoid more of the pain.

70
00:07:04,639 --> 00:07:09,447
If we just ponder for a moment, we come to realise that we don't actually know our bodies.

71
00:07:10,067 --> 00:07:20,382
For instance, we carefully comb our hair, we spend a lot of money at the barbers and hairdressers, but when one falls out, we never shed a tear, unless it becomes an epidemic, as it did with me.

72
00:07:22,064 --> 00:07:25,529
In fact, we don't have any feeling in the hair, in the hair itself.

73
00:07:26,752 --> 00:07:27,793
It's not just my hair.

74
00:07:28,233 --> 00:07:28,935
What of nails?

75
00:07:29,074 --> 00:07:29,495
Of blood?

76
00:07:29,956 --> 00:07:31,237
Do we feel our blood?

77
00:07:32,213 --> 00:07:37,620
Even when we cut ourselves and some flows out, do I feel the blood in itself flow out of me?

78
00:07:38,341 --> 00:07:40,906
Do I experience me flowing out with my blood?

79
00:07:41,726 --> 00:07:44,791
When the blood falls and hits the floor, do I shout, ouch?

80
00:07:46,555 --> 00:07:53,144
In Buddhist understanding, the mind by which I know things is only in contact with the material body through the senses.

81
00:07:53,966 --> 00:08:00,516
So although the cut signals pain, I do not experience each skin cell nor the blood that flows.

82
00:08:01,660 --> 00:08:03,521
The point of contact is the nerve ending.

83
00:08:04,442 --> 00:08:08,028
If the nerve goes numb or is destroyed, I don't feel the cut.

84
00:08:09,309 --> 00:08:11,973
What I know of my body is what I can sense, that's all.

85
00:08:13,314 --> 00:08:19,442
I can see its shape, hear the heartbeat, feel pleasurable and painful sensations and so on.

86
00:08:19,461 --> 00:08:24,747
I experience this through the different interactions and combinations of the four elements.

87
00:08:26,095 --> 00:08:32,066
When we meditate, especially if we do a long course of, say, a week, these elements can become quite obvious to us.

88
00:08:32,365 --> 00:08:36,173
We begin to see that they form a category of mental experience.

89
00:08:38,356 --> 00:08:42,565
The next category is the aggregate of sensations, called in Pali, Vedana.

90
00:08:43,527 --> 00:08:47,614
This is where we experience pleasurable, painful or neutral sensations.

91
00:08:48,572 --> 00:08:57,081
Whatever combinations of elements go to make up the original contact, this contact is experienced as pleasing, painful or neutral.

92
00:08:58,662 --> 00:09:02,105
When we chew an apple, a good juicy one, contacts are made all over the tongue.

93
00:09:03,366 --> 00:09:08,932
Each individual contact at the end of each taste bud on the tongue is experienced as sweet and tasty.

94
00:09:09,932 --> 00:09:17,500
All these sensations, and there's never a moment when the body is not sending sense data to the mind, can all be collected into one heap.

95
00:09:18,019 --> 00:09:19,461
the aggregate of sensation.

96
00:09:21,965 --> 00:09:28,754
The third aggregate, sannyā, is to do with that part of the mind that labels these sense objects.

97
00:09:28,774 --> 00:09:30,436
It includes all our perceptions.

98
00:09:31,758 --> 00:09:40,028
When air vibrations of a sound puts pressure on the eardrum, that pressure is mostly the earth element.

99
00:09:41,149 --> 00:09:47,638
This contact causes sensations to arise that are pleasant and that are then perceived as music.

100
00:09:48,158 --> 00:09:51,241
If the sensations are unpleasant, the sound is perceived as noise.

101
00:09:52,322 --> 00:09:57,931
If neither pleasant nor unpleasant sound is perceived, it's simply perceived as sound.

102
00:09:59,072 --> 00:10:07,062
Included then in the aggregate is not just the labelling of things, but also our value judgements, including all our biases and prejudices.

103
00:10:08,544 --> 00:10:12,570
The important thing for the meditator is to be able to listen to these perceptions objectively.

104
00:10:13,631 --> 00:10:16,274
And not only in the sitting posture, but throughout the day.

105
00:10:17,200 --> 00:10:22,267
If we heighten our general awareness, we come to know that many of our perceptions are subliminal.

106
00:10:22,427 --> 00:10:23,729
We are barely conscious of them.

107
00:10:24,910 --> 00:10:28,315
And we are often not conscious of how our perceptions are prejudiced.

108
00:10:29,115 --> 00:10:30,697
We take the way we think for granted.

109
00:10:32,059 --> 00:10:39,770
At base, then, this aggregate of perception, sannyā, is just a recognition of the object, but this recognition has built-in values.

110
00:10:40,711 --> 00:10:45,739
It is these value judgments that can be wrong, and so bring about suffering for others and ourselves.

111
00:10:46,023 --> 00:10:48,966
We need to investigate all our value judgments.

112
00:10:48,986 --> 00:10:52,072
We need to become more and more aware of the aggregate of perception.

113
00:10:54,695 --> 00:11:02,966
The next aggregate is called volitional formations or conditioning, sankhara, and refers to all those states of mind, negative and positive.

114
00:11:03,868 --> 00:11:05,650
It is all our emotions and moods.

115
00:11:06,731 --> 00:11:11,658
It is in this aggregate that we can say we experience the sufferings and the joys of life.

116
00:11:13,023 --> 00:11:20,871
It is one of the aims of meditation to cleanse this aggregate of all the negative states and move towards those states of mind the Buddha called the divine abodes.

117
00:11:21,673 --> 00:11:27,379
That is, abiding in loving kindness, compassion, sympathetic joy and equanimity.

118
00:11:29,282 --> 00:11:35,850
These volitional conditionings are that part of the mind that reacts to incoming data, sensations and perceptions.

119
00:11:37,152 --> 00:11:42,658
It is very important here for the meditator to grasp what is happening if such negativity is to be undermined.

120
00:11:43,600 --> 00:11:55,466
By negativity here, it simply meant all those states of mind that we experience as unpleasant, disagreeable and painful, like depression, anxiety, fear, frustration, guilt, sorrow, and so on.

121
00:11:57,370 --> 00:12:02,857
Jack sits in the armchair with a cup of tea after a hard day's work, finally enjoying a bit of peace and quiet.

122
00:12:03,438 --> 00:12:07,705
Suddenly, through the dividing wall, heavy rock comes bursting through from next door.

123
00:12:08,346 --> 00:12:11,070
The insistent thud beats its rhythm on Jack's eardrum.

124
00:12:11,770 --> 00:12:15,716
Feelings arise perceived as unpleasant.

125
00:12:15,881 --> 00:12:20,052
This perception of noise sharpens the focus and the reaction arises.

126
00:12:20,936 --> 00:12:24,886
This reaction is how Jack has taught himself to respond to such a perception.

127
00:12:25,548 --> 00:12:31,544
He's fuming with anger, more so because he's asked his neighbours not to play their musics aloud.

128
00:12:32,133 --> 00:12:35,239
Now at first glance it seems that Jack is justified in his anger.

129
00:12:35,960 --> 00:12:40,207
That his anger is caused by next door who are not being neighbourly.

130
00:12:40,969 --> 00:12:46,057
But is his anger really caused by their lack of neighbourliness or by the heavy rock?

131
00:12:47,039 --> 00:12:52,470
Or is his anger the way he's taught himself to react when he hears such a noise?

132
00:12:53,969 --> 00:13:04,282
This is a crucial point, and once we've grasped the mechanics here and actually see what is happening within ourselves, we will be able to make great headway in reducing the amount of emotional suffering we bear.

133
00:13:05,744 --> 00:13:12,331
This is one of the reasons for meditation, to become more and more aware of our passing moods, how they arise and how they pass away.

134
00:13:13,453 --> 00:13:23,166
This aggregate, translated as volitional formations or volitional conditionings, is precisely so called because these mental states are the product of our own will.

135
00:13:24,445 --> 00:13:26,388
Nobody has made Jack angry.

136
00:13:27,048 --> 00:13:29,033
Nothing at all, in fact, makes Jack angry.

137
00:13:29,493 --> 00:13:33,941
Jack's anger is his own learnt response, willed by him and him alone.

138
00:13:35,043 --> 00:13:46,621
When Jill, his teenage daughter, comes in looking for something, she quite unconsciously starts humming the tune, subliminally delighted by that very same noise that Jack, her dad, says ruins his tea.

139
00:13:48,576 --> 00:13:58,033
Indeed, if anger were caused by an outside object, then we could argue that there must be an object in the world that makes everyone angry as soon as they see or hear it.

140
00:13:58,534 --> 00:13:59,395
But this is not so.

141
00:14:00,238 --> 00:14:05,307
We all have our own conditioning, and individual conditionings have their own individual reactions.

142
00:14:06,589 --> 00:14:11,277
Now you might ask, well, how is it I get angry even when I don't mean to?

143
00:14:12,707 --> 00:14:20,756
If it is really all to do with me conditioning myself, if it is really all to do with my will, why don't I have immediate control?

144
00:14:22,437 --> 00:14:26,062
The fact is that will has conditioned this category of mind.

145
00:14:26,383 --> 00:14:27,543
Habits have been formed.

146
00:14:28,524 --> 00:14:36,994
That part of the mind which contains our emotional reactions and moods has been habituated, trained, conditioned to respond in certain ways.

147
00:14:37,884 --> 00:14:42,453
The first step to undermining this conditioning is to realize for ourselves the role of the will.

148
00:14:43,475 --> 00:14:49,989
Then we can see clearly that our emotions and moods are truly the result of past acts of will.

149
00:14:50,009 --> 00:14:55,860
We then realize that by refusing to will, to entertain these states of mind, they will pass away.

150
00:14:58,134 --> 00:15:00,879
Jack believes he is right to get angry with his neighbours.

151
00:15:01,119 --> 00:15:02,340
He believes it is justified.

152
00:15:02,821 --> 00:15:08,227
In fact, he's tricked himself into believing that the music and the neighbours themselves are directly causing his anger.

153
00:15:09,549 --> 00:15:15,518
So long as he believes this, every time anger arises because of the music and the neighbours, he will indulge that anger.

154
00:15:16,318 --> 00:15:20,344
When he indulges that anger, he is actually saying, yes, I will get angry.

155
00:15:21,485 --> 00:15:22,826
If only Jack would meditate.

156
00:15:23,498 --> 00:15:28,548
If he did, he would soon come to realize that it is he himself who wills his own anger.

157
00:15:29,330 --> 00:15:33,638
By refusing to will it, to indulge it, he will undermine his own learnt response.

158
00:15:34,299 --> 00:15:37,866
Eventually, he will come to perceive the noise as simply sound.

159
00:15:38,528 --> 00:15:43,076
He may even be influenced by his teenage daughter and come to recognize some musicality.

160
00:15:45,807 --> 00:15:59,046
When a meditator who has always believed that others were the cause of her or his anger, depression, stress and so on, realize that they are in fact self-taught responses, a great insight has been made.

161
00:15:59,726 --> 00:16:06,275
For from now on, the state of mind will come more and more under personal control.

162
00:16:07,638 --> 00:16:11,764
She realizes that she can control it, given time and ardent practice.

163
00:16:13,177 --> 00:16:14,740
This practice is twofold.

164
00:16:15,081 --> 00:16:21,931
Firstly, not to indulge in any negative states of mind, thereby allowing old conditioning to die out.

165
00:16:22,532 --> 00:16:28,399
Secondly, not to will any new negative states of mind, thereby keeping the mind pure.

166
00:16:29,522 --> 00:16:31,504
This is a very liberating insight.

167
00:16:34,269 --> 00:16:37,092
Finally, there is the aggregate of consciousness.

168
00:16:37,629 --> 00:16:46,663
This is the faculty in the mind that just cognizes, it knows, it is the mirror in which all the rest of the mind displays itself.

169
00:16:46,682 --> 00:16:52,672
This consciousness in meditation takes on the quality of awareness and objective viewing and knowing.

170
00:16:53,673 --> 00:17:01,764
From this standpoint of watching all the sensations, emotions, thoughts and imaginings, insight into the true nature of mind arises.

171
00:17:02,403 --> 00:17:07,089
This is the first step for the meditator, to become the impartial objective observer.

172
00:17:07,470 --> 00:17:11,516
Just knowing what's going on is enough for wisdom and insight to arise.

173
00:17:13,598 --> 00:17:14,381
So, to recap.

174
00:17:15,241 --> 00:17:18,967
The Buddha divided the human being into five aggregates or heaps.

175
00:17:19,428 --> 00:17:24,935
They are, firstly, matter and mind's initial contact with matter through the six senses.

176
00:17:25,317 --> 00:17:27,599
The sixth sense here being mind itself.

177
00:17:28,558 --> 00:17:33,424
Secondly, all the sensations experienced as pleasant, unpleasant are neutral.

178
00:17:34,385 --> 00:17:38,510
Thirdly, all the perceptions, recognitions, images and thoughts.

179
00:17:39,392 --> 00:17:43,016
Fourthly, all the mental states, our moods and emotions.

180
00:17:43,395 --> 00:17:47,101
And lastly, all our consciousnesses that know all this.

181
00:17:48,422 --> 00:17:53,587
The importance of these categorizations is that they help us to pinpoint where suffering arises.

182
00:17:54,698 --> 00:18:00,244
When I first walked around the streets in my robes, I was very much aware of people's reactions to this alien.

183
00:18:01,286 --> 00:18:05,391
One of the most difficult reactions for me to handle with equanimity was the look of disgust.

184
00:18:06,451 --> 00:18:08,673
Now, what actually happened to me on such an occasion?

185
00:18:10,236 --> 00:18:15,162
The retinas of my eyes simply respond to incoming light, that is, the simple contact.

186
00:18:15,702 --> 00:18:19,166
This light is conveyed to the mind where perception recognizes it.

187
00:18:19,606 --> 00:18:24,553
It is pigeonholed as woman with disgusted look with disgusted look at me.

188
00:18:25,106 --> 00:18:31,454
and with it, bad, meaning, no one should look at the noble likes of me with disgust.

189
00:18:32,717 --> 00:18:38,904
With the perception of a disgusted face, there arises in me the feelings of what these perceptions mean.

190
00:18:39,605 --> 00:18:41,669
I feel her disgust for me.

191
00:18:42,068 --> 00:18:42,769
I empathize.

192
00:18:44,271 --> 00:18:48,718
Unpleasant feelings fill my body, so this is what she feels for me.

193
00:18:49,491 --> 00:18:59,122
I now get angry because I believe that if someone is disgusted with me for no logical reason, from my point of view that is, I am justified in getting angry with that person.

194
00:19:00,182 --> 00:19:02,865
Who is she to feel disgust at me?

195
00:19:03,266 --> 00:19:04,267
Doesn't she know I'm a monk?

196
00:19:04,446 --> 00:19:04,988
How ignorant!

197
00:19:05,188 --> 00:19:06,108
It's disgusting.

198
00:19:07,430 --> 00:19:12,796
This disgust and the ensuing anger is simply how I've trained myself to respond to such looks.

199
00:19:13,876 --> 00:19:16,680
My consciousness totally identifies with this.

200
00:19:17,182 --> 00:19:18,728
This is the me, the ego.

201
00:19:19,691 --> 00:19:20,573
Anything can happen.

202
00:19:21,276 --> 00:19:26,109
Next morning, the headlines read, Buddhist monk breaks begging bowl on old woman's head.

203
00:19:26,672 --> 00:19:27,615
It's disgusting.

204
00:19:29,468 --> 00:19:42,740
Of course, it is hoped that the monk has learned his lesson, and that now realizing that the woman did not actually make him disgusted and angry, he understands that the woman's perception and feelings are her own too.

205
00:19:43,582 --> 00:19:47,244
That in truth, the more skillful response may have been a smile.

206
00:19:49,788 --> 00:19:52,529
Well, I hope you found this talk interesting and helpful.

207
00:19:53,692 --> 00:19:55,593
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

208
00:19:56,253 --> 00:19:59,356
May all of you attain the nirvanic peace within.

